This is Tom Ate

Tom Ate is a well-known filmmaker who is now working on a new big production. The film will be about a love story between two young men in the Second World War, but he still needs to find the perfect cast.

Two actors in their late twenties with experience in belic, romance, and/or drama films, with many connections within the film industry to help the promotion of the movie ... and it would be a plus if they have previously worked together.

But how could Tom Ate find these actors in the most accurate and efficient way?

Network and text analysis tools can help creating an advanced actor database that could be used by casting directors and marketing agencies to find the best profiles for a specific cinematographic project or campaign. This database could include features such as:

What are the words that best describe a profile based on previous work? Analyzing movie reviews, scripts, or plots, could help us in identifying the terms that best describe an actor's career. These words may include relevant character names or terms that match to specific semantic fields.

What's the sentiment towards a profile based on reviews? We could determine the general public's impression of an actor's work based on reviews of all those films in which they have appeared.

Is this profile central with respect to the others? We can discover actors who are central in the actor network by analyzing the relationships with other actors based on the movies they have acted in together, which may suggest an actor's ability to perform different roles or provide casting directors an estimate of their popularity.

What are the profiles for which a specific word (or collection of words) is more relevant with respect to other profiles? Text analysis allows us to determine the relevance of a word for different actors. Therefore, when looking for actors related to a specific word in a database, we could implement the results of text analysis to order search results so that the first actors will be more related to that specific term.

And many more ...

What is this project about?

We would like to see how network and text analysis can help casting directors and marketing agencies improve their actor databases and recommender systems. To do so, we conduct a small-scale investigation into the network of actors who have appeared in the highest-rated films over the last five decades.

Analyzing the complete network of movies and actors has limitations in terms of computation time. Moreover, by choosing only those actors who appear in the top-rated movies from the 70s on, we can draw conclusions based on a network of meaningful connections. This way we start with some assumptions about the data that will help us to better understand the results.

Data Sources

The first data source used in this project is IMDb. IMDb is an online database that includes cast, production crew, and personal biographies, plot summaries, ratings, and fan and critical reviews for films, television programs, home videos, video games, and streaming material online.

In order to build our dataset, we got the top 1000 rated movies in IMDb from 1970 on, with more than 100000 votes and with an average rating greater than or equal to 7. To construct our final dataset with top movies, we first merged two datasets: one with all titles in IMDb that included basic information such as release year and movie genres; and another dataset that included ratings.

Once we had all the movies we were interested in, we moved to our second data source, Moviepedia. Moviepedia is a crowdsourced encyclopedia containing over 25000 articles about current and past movies, as well as those that are planned or in preparation. Their goal is gather movie enthusiasts to create a dependable, accurate resource with as much information about movies as possible.

Our goal was to use this data source to extract movie plot and cast information, and we ran into the first obstacle in this process. Some of the film titles were missing in Movipedia, while others had a different name than the one in IMDb. We developed an algorithm that was able to extract around 800 movies out of 1000:

1st try. Perfect match ü§ù : Some IMDb movie titles were also found on Moviepedia, so we just took the text contained in the corresponding Moviepedia page. If the length of the content was too short, it meant that either no information was available or that we couldn't extract enough data from the film. These films would be discarded.

2nd try. Lost twin üëØ: We noticed that adding the release year between parenthesis to some IMDb movies, such as Gladiator/ Gladiator (2000), allowed us to reunite the twins. If no perfect match could be found, we would use this method to find the equivalent title in Moviepedia and extract the content.

3rd try. CSI üïµÔ∏è: If the previous attempts have failed, then we would use the Moviepedia search tool. We were able to extract some additional movies by searching for the IMDb title using the Moviepedia search engine, getting the first results, and finding the result that best matches the original title. The content would then be extracted in the same manner as before.

Once we had Moviepedia page content for most of the initial collection of movies, we wanted to extract both the plot and the cast from the raw text. We managed to extract the plot for around 500 movies, since some of them either didn't have the section corresponding to the plot, or the plot content was too short.

We also wanted to get the cast from the raw text. However, due to non-standard formatting of cast across pages, extracting the cast for each film became impossible, and most actor pages lacked relevant information such as birth date, birth place, and biography. We needed another solution, and that solution was again provided by IMDb.

The IMDb API provides information about each film's cast members, which are organized by relevance. This API also provides information about each actor, including his or her birthplace, date of birth, and a brief biography. In comparison to the 1000 actors we were able to extract using Moviepedia, this allowed us to obtain information for around 3500 actors.

But don't think we took the easy way out! As described in the data extraction notebook, we used both methods and compared the results. In the case of using the cast from Moviepedia, we still had to find the information for each actor. To do so, we retrieved this information from Wikipedia API. However, because not all actors were present there, the network's total number of actors would have been reduced even further. As a result, we chose IMDb as our primary data source for cast.

We ended up with three datasets that we used for network and text analysis:

Top movies dataset: This dataset contains basic information about those titles for which we were able to obtain the plot. IMDb title, Moviepedia title, IMDb API id, rating, plot, and reviews, are some of the columns this dataset contains.

Cast dataset: This dataset contains information about the actors that play in each of the movies of the previous dataset. It associates the actor's id with the film in which they appeared.

Actors dataset This dataset contains information about actors that play in the movies of the first dataset. Actor's name, birth date, birth place, gender, biography, average rating, or number of appearances are some of the columns this dataset contains.

Basic Stats

A network of approximately 3500 actors was created, with two actors being linked if they starred in the same film. After obtaining all possible combinations of actors from the cast dataset, about 30000 links were established between the actors. The number of times two actors have coincided was utilized to assign a weight to the relationship. This way, as two actors are professionally closer, their connection becomes stronger.

Demography

We to take a closer look at the demographics of the actors. How equally distributed are age, gender, and birth places?

Looking at the pictured plots above, we can conclude: most of the actors are born in the US or another English-speaking country. The age seems slightly skewed normal distributed, where the average year of birth is around 1960, i.e. the average age is around 50 . The distribution does not take into account that some of the actors might be already dead. There are twice as many men as women and around 500 actors for whom we do not know their gender.

Further, we are interested in the types of movies that are among the top movie list. The following figure depicts the number of actors playing in a certain genre:

The most frequent genres among the top-rated movies are drama, adventure, action and comedy . More niche genres as western, musical and sport are very rare. That could be explained by the fact that they attract rather a specific audience, whereas the more frequent genres address a broader audience.

The network

Take a look at the network of actors. Pretty, isn't it? But maybe a little confusing ...

Still, we can already see that some of the actors are pretty good connected in the network, whereas other actors have only very few links to other actors. We can see that there are small niches that may correspond to movie casts. In this sense, most of the members of the different casts are not so well-connected, while they always have one or two members more central in the network, which may be the main actors of the movie.

To state it more quantitatively we dig into network analysis and find out: (1) The network has 3419 nodes and 29588 links; (2) The minimum degree is 6 and the maximum degree is 148 . That doesn‚Äôt tell us much about the structure of the network . More insights provide the degree distribution:

We see clearly actors have links to around 8 to 12 other actors. The amount of actors with more than around 15 neighbor actors decreases immediately. The log-scaled plot on the right side indicates that the network is similar to a scale-free network, as the degree distribution seems to follow a power law. This means, we have few so-called superhubs among the actors, that have an immensely high amount of neighbors, while most of the actors have only a few neighbors.

But who are the superhubs in our actor network, e.g. which actors have the highest node degree? And are they actually among the most popular actors in Hollywood? It‚Äôs your turn! Do you know the names of those five actors in the following image?

If yes, the network did a good job, as those five actors with the highest node degree represent some of the most famous actors. (If you don‚Äôt know them, we highly recommend you to start watching iconic movies like Forrest Gump, Pulp Fiction, The Godfather or Inception to get to know those actors).

We solve the riddle: those above depicted actors are Samuel L. Jackson (node degree 127) , Robert De Niro (148), Tom Hanks (127), Al Pacino (120), Leonardo DiCaprio (115). Did you know that the su^perhub of our network ‚Äì Robert De Niro ‚Äì is not : He was born in the United States but was also awarded honorary citizenship by Italy in 2004.

Let‚Äôs look at the distribution of the link weights:

The distribution of the edge weights seems to follow a power law as well, as the distribution seems linear in the above plot with a log-scaled y-axis.

Centrality Analysis

Robert De Niro is the actor with the highest node degree. But how connected are the actors he played together with. Or in other words, how central is Robert De Niro in our network of actors?

To answer such a question we make use of centrality measures. ‚ÄØThose centrality measures assign numbers to nodes corresponding to their position in the network. The more "central" a node is, the higher is its number. In our network, centrality measures can help us identifying the most influential and popular actors.

Degree centralitiy‚ÄØmeasures the number of edges to other nodes, e.g. with how many other actors each actor collaborated in the top movies. The five actors with the highest degree centrality correspond to the actors with the highest node degree. That is, Robert De Niro has the highest degree centrality, followed by Samuel L. Jackson, Tom Hanks, Al Pacino and Leonardo Di Caprio.

The‚ÄØcloseness centrality‚ÄØof a node is the average length of the shortest path between the node and all other nodes in the graph. In Our network Leonardo DiCaprio has the highest closeness centrality, followed by Samuel L. Jackson, Tom Hanks, Bonnie Hunt and Mark Ruffalo.

Comparing degree with closeness centrality yields interesting insights: Robert De Niro has the highest degree centrality, but not the highest closeness centrality. This means that he has played together with the highest number of other actors. However, those other neihgboring actors have a comparably bad centrality compared to other actors. A possibe explanation might be that Robert De Niro is a rather old actor and our network relies on "younger" movies released after 1970. Another explanation might be, that he collaborated mainly with unknown actors in his movies.

Sentiment Analysis

Some actors tend to play certain roles in movies. Javier Bardem, Christoph Waltz, or Ralph Fiennes, for example, are famous for playing evil characters. Other actors as, for example, Eddie Murphy or Adam Sandler are famous for their roles in comedies. We are interested in the actor‚Äòs characteristics of their roles . But how to classify actors based on the movies they are famous for?

We compute the sentiment of the extracted plots of the movies as well as the user reviews for all movies. We then assign for every actor the average sentiment of the movies an actor played in. We hope that this sentiment helps, to find actors, based on their sentiment. Are you looking for an evil actor? Or rather for a funny actor?

We compute the sentiment with VADER . VADER is a tool for sentiment analysis that uses a rule-based approach. That means the sentiment of a sentence does not consist only of the average sentiment of its words. Besides a dictionary that contains sentiment scores for more than 10000 words (assessed by first year psychology students), some rules lead to a change of the sentiment of the sentence if certain words or expressions are contained. The following five rules are considered in VADER:

1st. An increase of the sentiment intensity by punctuation , namely the exclamation point. For example: ‚ÄúThe food here is good!!!‚Äù is more intense than ‚ÄúThe food here is good.‚Äù

2nd. An increase of the sentiment intensity by using ALL-CAPS to "emphasize a sentiment-relevant word in the presence of other non-capitalized words". For example "The food is SO GOOD" is more intense than "The food is so good".

3rd. An increase or decrease of the intensity by degree modifiers (for example "extremely", "really", "barely", "marginally").‚ÄØ

4th. Shift in the sentiment polarity by the contrastive conjunction ‚Äúbut‚Äù . For example the sentiment of "The food is good." differs from the sentiment of "The food is good but too expensive."

5th. Shift in the sentiment polarity by negations . For example in "The food is not good".

Let‚Äôs take a look at some results: The five most positive movies regarding their plots sentiment are ‚ÄúSouthpaw‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe French Connection‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe Master‚Äù, ‚ÄúLove Actually‚Äù and ‚ÄúThe Fault in Our Stars‚Äù. The five most negative are ‚ÄúSaw‚Äù, ‚ÄúInsomnia‚Äù, ‚ÄúThe invisible Man‚Äù, ‚ÄúShutter Island‚Äù and ‚ÄúHacksaw Ridge‚Äù. Well, Southpaw is a sport drama and apparently neither really funny nor positive. Apart from that, the sentiment seems to give insights to the overall sentiment of the movies, as mainly comedies are among the most positive and mainly horror movies are among the most negative movies.

Looking at the distribution of the sentiments for the actors, we can conclude that the scores of the negative sentiment are on average higher than those of the positive. That means the actor‚Äôs dominant attribute tend to be negative. It could be interpreted in the way, that the actors of our network tend to play in rather dramatic and sad movies.

Community Analysis

The network we provide here is already enormous, yet it includes only top of the top. Of course, every actor has a set of unique characteristics that make them less or more suitable for certain movies. Looking at the so many of them at once enables us to find similarities between some and group them by one common characteristic.

To do so, we gather information on actors and group them by similarities. The groups of actors that share a characteristic, like number of movies they appeared in or the country they come from, are called communities. We throughly investigate those and we notice that the best division (in terms of quality) is when we use actor‚Äôs sentiment related to the plots. However, it just confirms that the bunch of sad actors played altogether in sad movies, is it helpful though?

To enrich the outcome of our analysis and increase its accuracy, we turn to deeper scientific approaches, particularly to a mystery louvain method. We finally want to uncover the communities of actors who are strongly linked to each other and there is a scientific basis for that. Let us walk you through an example:

First, see which actors are supposed to be similar - they share a colour on the graph:

Graph help: The Degree characteristic can be interpreted as the popularity of an actor within this network, while the size of the node indicates how many movies they starred in. It‚Äôs easy to spot the most appearing actors, but other than that the graph is quite overwhelming to see any patterns, there are 28 different communities!

And this is the representation of all the communities as nodes:

To dig deeper, we choose the smallest and the biggest community, we investigate how are actors in each of them related.

BTW that‚Äôs how the size of the communities varies:

That‚Äôs the example of trends for those communities:

The visualization of the biggest community include all of the members actors, it can be visible that some of them seem to be more ‚Äòprivileged‚Äô and they hold the small sub-communities together. Who are other actors that seem to be outliers? They just star in the same movies with more popular actors and that‚Äôs why they are dragged into one community, but their influence seems so much smaller‚Ä¶

In this case, Tom Hanks is the actor who appeared the most times, but it is Jack Angel who has way more connections. Who is he? Why has nobody heard of him? He is the dubbing voice! (Take a look at the visual including his photo :) He is a real star.

The smallest community we explore is a cluster of South Korean actors that shared some movies, is it why they are such a connected group? Probably yes, another time, no surprise, BUT what if a director would like to do very specific movie, e.g. focused on particular culture or theme.

As graph shows, small communities might take different shapes, but the pattern of more popular actors holding together the rest repeats.

LDA and Topic Modelling

As much as we would like to use the sentiments to group actors and describe their profiles, the scientific tools are not advanced enough to give us the desired results. Neither plots nor reviews have an interesting sentiment distribution and besides that we would prefer to have more sentiment values, such as happy, angry, sad etc. This could really help the director distinct between actors.

However, to give science a chance, we utilise the texts of the plots once more - this time we refer to them as documents. Our last approach is to try to extract topics and also the words that belong to the plots (that in turn belong to the actors).

Linking the topics together with actors results in assigning a ‚Äòmain topic‚Äô to each actor and then dividing them according to the common topics (exactly, we have the communities once again).

Let‚Äôs start with introducing the basics from our findings:

We have 28 different topics and each actor has always one main topic. Apparently one topic is dominating (the graph shows the number of actors that have each topic as main):

All of the words for each topic can be checked here below (so interactive ;)

Last but not least, which actors are so close together and share the topic 26 and who is an outsider? Check below:

We see that the words belonging to each topic are very specific (sometimes too specific). The documents we analyse are quite long and we only take into account ‚Äòsignificant‚Äô words when describing the topics. Some interesting examples in our study case: perish, furious, synthetic body, redoubling or snare. The beauty of the terms variety is that you choose which of them are useful and meaningful for your movie. If the movie is just a simple novel you opt for basics such as ‚Äòpeace‚Äô or ‚Äòwished‚Äô, whereas the movie with a particular topic could require the terms such as ‚Äòaquaphobia‚Äô or ‚Äòbank account‚Äô.

TF-IDF and Wordclouds

The TF-IDF is a statistical measure that can be used to determine the importance of a word to a document in a collection of documents. In this sense, if two terms occur in a document equally frequently, the word that occurs less frequently throughout the collection of papers is considered more relevant to that document.

Depending on the goal of our analysis, we can construct a document for each actor that includes text of plots from movies in which the actor has performed, scripts, reviews, or bios. Then, by applying TF-IDF we could find the words that best characterize an actor in comparison to the rest of actors in terms of specific movie genres (words belonging to certain semantic fields), characters, personal life, or public opinion.

And how could we implement the results in the f a n c y actor database?

Order search results: If someone wants to find the actor(s) associated with a specific term or set of terms, we could order search results based on the TF-IDF scores of these terms for the different actors. As a result, actors who are more closely related to that term or terms will appear first.

Actor's career overview: Results from¬†TF-IDF can be displayed as Wordclouds, which can be included in an actor's profile to provide visitors a quick overview of previous works.

Plots by actor

The plots of the films in which an actor features were compiled into a single document. Then we used TF-IDF to find the most relevant words for each actor and used wordclouds to display the results. Our goal was to discover terms for each actor that belonged to specific semantic fields, so that a casting director could later search for actors who matched a given plot or movie genre better. To do so, we removed character names from the plots, however this was not possible in many cases.

Tom Hanks

Scarlet Johansson

Leonardo Di Caprio

Morgan Freeman

Since we didn't manage to remove all the characters and these are, of course, frequent in a document but not in every document, then these occupy the first positions of the TF-IDF ranking. Therefore, we can still identify relevant character names (played or associated) for each actor such as Woody (Toy Story) or Bubba (Forrest Gump) for Tom Hanks, Romanoff (Avengers) for Scarlet Johansson, or Batman for Morgan Freeman.

In the same way, we can identify some relevant words related to each actor: feather, shrimp, Alabama , destiny (Forrest Gump) for Tom Hanks; horseman, cowboy, whiskey, gunfighter (Django) for Morgan Freeman; and limbo, dream, projection, subconscious (Inception) for Leonardo Di Caprio. Results could be improved with a more advanced preprocessing that eliminates all character names.

Reviews by actor

The top reviews of the films in which an actor features were compiled into a single document. Then we used TF-IDF to find the most relevant words for each actor and used wordclouds to display the results. Our goal was to get a sense of how people perceive an actor's work based on the words that people use in the reviews. To do so, we removed character names from the reviews as we did with plots, however this was not possible in many cases. For this reason, an unexpectedly, we found out that we could also use reviews to characterize an actor's career, since these reviews contained the most relevant words for each film such as character names, places, or words belonging to specific semantic fields.

Tom Hanks

Scarlet Johansson

Leonardo Di Caprio

Morgan Freeman

Results can be considered as informative as those obtained after analyzing the plots. We can identify some relevant words related to the roles of each actor: pirate, cargo, somali, lifeboat, Phillip, navy (Captain Philip) for Tom Hanks; or joker, gotham, batman (Batman) for Morgan Freeman. Depending on the preprocessing, we could achieve different goals: by removing character, director, and actor names, we could identify sentiment or role descriptive words; by leaving them we can identify characters, actors, directors, and words relevant to an actor.
